Fig. 4 compares the capabilities of pedestrian detection. We notice that the detection probability of the perception system in LOS ﬁts well to the theoretical curve. On the other hand, although the curves have similar shapes for the communication system, the gap between the experimental and theoretical curves are large due to the high packets loss experienced during the tests. We believe that this is due to the processing overhead of the software.
The detection capabilities are poorer in the NLOS scenario for both the communication and perception systems. This is especially signiﬁcant for the perception system: the detection distance is reduced to 40 m and the probability of detection stays below 70% due to the occlusion. For the V2P communication, the performance is largely degraded for the distances farther than 60 m.
To summarize, the perception system excels in detecting a pedestrian for the distances smaller than 50 m, while the communication performs better for the distances larger than 80 m.

